# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2008-beijing-wushu-tournament
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The **1936 Summer Olympics** (German: *Olympische Sommerspiele 1936*), officially the **Games of the XI Olympiad** (German: *Spiele der XI.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Olympiade*) and branded as **Berlin 1936**, were an international multi-sport event held from 1 to 16 August 1936 in Berlin, Germany.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Berlin won the right to host the Games over Barcelona at the 29th IOC Session in 1931.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The 1936 Games were the second and last occasion on which the International Olympic Committee (IOC) chose a host by a ballot in which the bidding cities themselves could vote; later rules barred cities that hosted the vote from being selected.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Games had been awarded to Germany during the Weimar Republic, but by 1936 the country was governed by the Nazi regime, and Adolf Hitler's government treated the Olympics as an opportunity for propaganda.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] To project an image of a peaceful, tolerant Germany, the authorities temporarily removed antisemitic signage and softened the most visible forms of persecution for the duration of the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] At the same time, the German Olympic authorities barred nearly all Jewish and Romani athletes from the national team; the fencer Helene Mayer, who had one Jewish parent, was the only such athlete to represent Germany.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] A movement to boycott or relocate the Games developed in several countries—Czechoslovakia, France, the Netherlands, Sweden, the United Kingdom, and the United States—but it ultimately failed.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Forty-nine nations competed, the largest number at any Olympics to that point.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] These were the first Games to be televised and the first to feature a torch relay carrying the Olympic flame from Olympia to the host city—a ceremony devised for Berlin that became a permanent Olympic tradition.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The filmmaker Leni Riefenstahl recorded the Games for her two-part film *Olympia*, which pioneered techniques still used in sports cinematography.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Jesse Owens of the United States won four gold medals in the sprint and long jump events, and became the most successful athlete to compete in Berlin, while Germany was the most successful country overall with 101 medals (38 of them gold); the United States placed a distant second with 57 medals.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] These were the final Olympic Games under the IOC presidency of Henri de Baillet-Latour.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] For the next 12 years, no Olympic Games were held due to the immense world disruption caused by the Second World War.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The next Olympic Games were held in 1948 (the Winter Games in St.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Moritz, Switzerland, and then the Summer Games in London, England).
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] At the 28th IOC Session in Berlin in May 1930, fourteen cities indicated an intention to bid for the 1936 Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] By the 29th Session, held in Barcelona in April 1931, only Barcelona and Berlin remained in contention; the other cities—Alexandria, Budapest, Buenos Aires, Cologne, Dublin, Frankfurt, Helsinki, Lausanne, Montevideo, Nuremberg, Rio de Janeiro, and Rome—had withdrawn.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Several of these cities later hosted the Games: Helsinki in 1952, Rome in 1960, Barcelona in 1992 and Rio de Janeiro in 2016.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The 1936 Games were the first for which the host was decided by a vote of each individual IOC member rather than by the assembled Session alone.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The deadline for ballots was 13 May 1931, two weeks after the Barcelona Session.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Of 67 voting members, 19 cast ballots during the Session and 40 by post to the IOC headquarters in Lausanne; eight abstained.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The result was 43 votes for Berlin and 16 for Barcelona.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Barcelona's prospects were probably weakened by the political uncertainty that followed the proclamation of the Second Spanish Republic days before the Session.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] After the Nazi seizure of power in 1933 and the regime's early antisemitic measures, some IOC members privately discussed moving the Games, and the US Olympic Association briefly suggested transferring them to Rome.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Hitler's government gave assurances that Jewish athletes would not be excluded from the German team, and the proposal was not seriously pursued.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Awarded to Berlin in 1931 under the Weimar Republic, the Games took on a new character after the Nazi takeover of January 1933, as the regime grasped their value as international propaganda.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Hitler regarded the Games as a chance to promote his government and its ideology of Aryan supremacy.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The official Nazi paper, the *Völkischer Beobachter*, had argued in the strongest terms that Jewish and black athletes should be barred from the Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] As the Games approached, however, the regime worked to soften Germany's international image: signs reading "Jews not welcome" (German: *Juden unerwünscht*) were taken down from public places for the duration, and overt antisemitic agitation was muted.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The effort extended to the removal of people the regime considered undesirable.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] In July 1936 the Ministry of the Interior authorised Berlin's police to detain the city's Romani and confine them in a special camp at Marzahn, on the city's outskirts.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Five months before the opening ceremony, in March 1936, Germany had remilitarised the Rhineland in breach of the Treaty of Versailles, heightening international tension in the months before the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] In line with Nazi directives, the German Olympic Committee effectively barred German athletes who were Jewish or Roma, or of such ancestry, from competing.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The most prominent excluded athlete was the high jumper Gretel Bergmann, who was dropped from the team shortly after equalling the German record of 1.60 m in June 1936.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Others kept off the team included the record-holding track-and-field athlete Lilli Henoch, the tennis player Daniel Prenn, the boxer Erich Seelig and the Sinti boxer Johann Trollmann.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Helene Mayer—already an Olympic champion who had emigrated to the United States—returned to fence for Germany and won a silver medal, the only athlete of Jewish descent on the German team, a token inclusion intended to deflect foreign criticism.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The exclusions also reached the organisers.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Although the Olympic flame had been reintroduced at the 1928 Summer Olympics, Berlin staged the first torch relay, carrying a flame kindled at Olympia in Greece to the host city through seven countries.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The concept, organised by Diem, established the modern convention later used at every Games, and Riefenstahl incorporated the relay into *Olympia*.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Olympic Village lay at Elstal in Wustermark, about 30 km west of central Berlin, and comprised low dormitories, a large "Dining Hall of the Nations", training facilities and a swimming hall.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] After the Games the site was absorbed by the Wehrmacht and later used by Soviet forces as a military camp; parts of it, including the dormitory used by Jesse Owens, have been restored more recently.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Twenty-two venues were used, most of them in the purpose-built Reichssportfeld complex, which had been planned for the cancelled 1916 Summer Olympics and was completed in 1934–36.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The centrepiece Olympic Stadium seated about 100,000; sailing was held in the Bay of Kiel, later reused for the 1972 Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Games were the first to be carried on live television.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Using Telefunken equipment, the German Post Office transmitted more than 70 hours of black-and-white coverage to public viewing rooms in Berlin and Potsdam, where more than 162,000 people in all followed the competitions on screens outside the stadium.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Radio carried the Games more widely still, in 28 languages across some 2,500 broadcasts.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Games were also an early showcase for colour photography, using Germany's newly developed Agfacolor film.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The filmmaker Leni Riefenstahl recorded the Games for her two-part documentary *Olympia*, released in 1938.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Games were among the most lavish staged to that point, and most of the spending lay well outside the organising committee's own accounts.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The organisers had originally budgeted the Games at about 4 million Reichsmark, to be raised through a three-year Olympic lottery, surcharged Olympic postage stamps and an "Olympic Penny" added to admission tickets at sporting events across Germany.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The stamps alone had been forecast to raise one million Reichsmark; in the event they brought in considerably more.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] From 1933 the Reich Ministry of the Interior directed a vast building programme that the regime folded into its public-works and job-creation schemes, and historians have treated this state investment—rather than ticket income—as the truer measure of what the Games cost.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Its centrepiece, the new Olympic Stadium, was built in barely two years at a cost of around 42 million Reichsmark; with the wider Reichssportfeld, the Olympic Village and new transport links, the state's outlay dwarfed the committee's budget.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Hitler also prized the Games as a way to earn scarce foreign currency at a time of dwindling German reserves, later claiming they had brought in large sums.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The committee's own books were comparatively modest: ticket sales brought in about 7.5 million RM and an operating profit of over one million RM.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The city of Berlin reported costs of about 16.5 million RM, while the national government's total spending was never published in full and has been estimated at around US$30 million.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Games also attracted commercial advertising: Coca-Cola's German subsidiary supplied the drink and promoted it heavily in Berlin during the Games, and the company's own account of its Olympic partnerships lists it as a sponsor of the 1936 Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Berlin confectioner Hildebrand introduced its caffeinated chocolate Scho-Ka-Kola at the Games, marketing it as a "sport chocolate" (German: *Sportschokolade*).
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Winter Games at Garmisch-Partenkirchen earlier that year had featured some of the first official commercial arrangements at an Olympics, with Coca-Cola acting as a sponsor and Ovaltine designated the "official drink".
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The sporting programme ran from 1 to 16 August 1936 and was framed by elaborate opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony took place at the Olympic Stadium on 1 August 1936.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The airship *Hindenburg* flew over the stadium trailing the Olympic flag.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] After Hitler's arrival the parade of nations proceeded, with Greece first and the host nation last; some teams gave the Nazi salute or the similar Olympic salute as they passed Hitler's box, while the United States and a few others did not.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Greek team that led the parade was headed by Spyridon Louis, winner of the marathon at the first modern Olympics in 1896, who presented Hitler with an olive branch from Olympia.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Hitler then declared the Games open; in keeping with Olympic protocol his part was confined to the set formula—"I proclaim the Games of Berlin, celebrating the eleventh Olympiad of the modern era, to be open"—his only public statement during the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] A torch-bearer then ran into the arena to light the cauldron, and thousands of pigeons were released.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] During the ceremony the Olympic Hymn—specially composed by Richard Strauss, who conducted it himself—received its première; Strauss had taken the commission only after the writer Gerhart Hauptmann failed to supply a text, and he privately dismissed the piece even as he led it.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The programme comprised 129 events in 25 disciplines across 19 sports.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Basketball, canoeing and handball made their Olympic debuts; handball would not return until the 1972 Summer Olympics, while polo made its fifth and final Olympic appearance.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Baseball and gliding were held as demonstration sports, and art competitions awarded medals, as did feats of alpinism and aeronautics recognised at the closing ceremony.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] National strengths were pronounced across the individual sports.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The host nation owed its place atop the medal table chiefly to gymnastics, rowing and the equestrian events, in which German riders won all six golds.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Athletics, the largest sport, was dominated by the United States, whose men won twelve track-and-field golds; Helen Stephens took two of the six women's events.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] In the pool the men's programme became a duel between the US and Japan, while Rie Mastenbroek of the Netherlands, the outstanding swimmer of the Games, led Dutch dominance of the women's events; US women instead won both diving titles.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] France's Robert Charpentier won three cycling golds, and the fencing titles fell mainly to Italy and Hungary.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The team events produced their own milestones.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The United States won the first Olympic basketball tournament, beating Canada 19–8 in a final played outdoors on a rain-soaked clay court, with the game's inventor James Naismith on hand to present the medals.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Germany won the inaugural field handball competition, an eleven-a-side outdoor game, and Hungary took the water polo, a sport it would go on to dominate.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Italy won the football and India a third successive hockey gold, while polo, won by Argentina, was contested for the last time.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The outstanding individual performer was Jesse Owens of the United States, who won gold in the 100 m, 200 m, long jump, and 4×100 m relay.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] In the long jump his German rival Luz Long offered him advice after he nearly failed to qualify, and the two were publicly cordial.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Mack Robinson, brother of Jackie Robinson, took 200 m silver behind Owens.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] In the 800 m, John Woodruff won gold after deliberately slowing to free himself when boxed in.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Jack Lovelock of New Zealand won the 1500 m in a world-record 3:47.8.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] In the decathlon, Glenn Morris of the United States set a world record of 7,900 points to lead an American medal sweep, and Ondina Valla took the 80 m hurdles to become the first Italian woman to win an Olympic title, in a final so close that the first four finishers were given the same time.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] German athletes were strong in several sports, sweeping all six equestrian golds and, in the gymnasts Konrad Frey and Alfred Schwarzmann, producing two triple gold medallists.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The equestrian team eventing title owed much to Konrad von Wangenheim, who finished the cross-country phase despite breaking his collarbone in a fall and returned the next day—his arm in a sling—to complete the jumping after he and his horse fell again.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Rie Mastenbroek of the Netherlands won three swimming golds and a silver, and the Estonian Kristjan Palusalu became the only wrestler to win both the freestyle and Greco-Roman heavyweight titles at a single Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Egyptian weightlifter Khadr El Touni won the middleweight gold with a world-record total, beating the German silver medallist by a wide margin.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] In the football tournament, Italy—coached by Vittorio Pozzo between their two FIFA World Cup wins—took gold; the result was claimed by supporters of Benito Mussolini as a vindication of fascism.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Peru had beaten Austria 4–2 after extra time amid a disputed pitch invasion, but the IOC ordered a replay behind closed doors; Peru refused and withdrew from the Games, as did Colombia in sympathy.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] On its Olympic football debut, Japan came from two goals down to beat the favoured Swedes 3–2 before being eliminated by Italy in the next round.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] India won its third consecutive hockey gold, defeating Germany 8–1 in the final.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] In the marathon, the Korean runners Sohn Kee-chung and Nam Sung-yong won gold and bronze while competing for Japan, which then ruled Korea.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] More than half a century later, Sohn carried the Olympic flame into the stadium at the 1988 Summer Olympics in Seoul.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The United States eight, from the University of Washington, won the rowing title with a come-from-behind final, later recounted in *The Boys in the Boat*.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The 13-year-old US Marjorie Gestring won the 3 m springboard, and Betty Robinson, the 1928 100 m champion who had nearly died in a 1931 plane crash, returned to win gold in the 4×100 m relay.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The American Jewish sprinters Marty Glickman and Sam Stoller were dropped from the 4×100 m relay on the morning of the race in favour of Owens and Ralph Metcalfe; the decision has been widely attributed to a wish not to embarrass the German hosts, though the reasons remain disputed.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Games closed on the evening of 16 August 1936 before a crowd of more than 100,000 in the Olympic Stadium.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Historians have described the closing as more sombre and militaristic than the opening, marked by columns of soldiers and fireworks.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] As the ceremony reached its climax, searchlights ringed the arena to form a "dome of light" overhead, the five-ringed Olympic flag was slowly lowered, and the flame that had burned since 1 August was extinguished as the spectators joined in a closing choral hymn.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] IOC president Henri de Baillet-Latour formally declared the Games closed.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] These were the last Olympics of his presidency and, as it proved, the last for twelve years; the 1940 Games had already been awarded to Tokyo at the IOC session held in Berlin on 31 July 1936, before the Olympics even opened.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Two unusual special awards were also recognised in connection with the closing.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] An Olympic gold for alpinism went to the mountaineers Günter and Hettie Dyhrenfurth for their Himalayan expeditions, and the only Olympic gold ever awarded for aeronautics went to the Swiss pilot Hermann Schreiber for the first glider flight across the Alps; neither prize was contested again.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Forty-nine nations competed, up from 37 in 1932.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Five made their first Olympic appearance: Afghanistan, Bermuda, Bolivia, Costa Rica and Liechtenstein.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Several nations returned after missing 1932, while Ireland and Spain competed in 1932 but were absent from Berlin.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Sources give the number of participants differently, largely because of how the art competitions are counted.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee gives the figure of 3,963 athletes—3,632 men and 331 women—in the sporting events.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The twelve nations that won the most medals at the 1936 Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] As at every Games from 1912 to 1948, medals were also awarded in art competitions for works inspired by sport.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The 1936 edition was the largest the Olympics ever staged, with fifteen events across five categories—architecture, literature, music, painting and sculpture—and the entries were shown in an exhibition on the Kaiserdamm that drew some 70,000 visitors.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] A novelty that year was that the prize-winning musical works were performed: the German composer Werner Egk took the orchestral gold for his *Olympic Festive Music*.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] With many French and British artists staying away, German entrants dominated, winning twelve of the thirty-two medals and five of the nine golds; the judges withheld medals entirely in three events.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The art competitions were dropped after 1948; the IOC currently recognises them as official, and its database gives Germany a combined total of 101 medals for the 1936 Games, including the 12 won in the art competitions.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Prior to and during the Games, there was considerable debate outside Germany over whether the competition should be allowed or discontinued.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] A number of campaigns to boycott or relocate the Games emerged in the United Kingdom, France, Sweden, Czechoslovakia, the Netherlands, and the United States.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The most consequential debate took place in the United States.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The protests were ultimately unsuccessful; forty-nine teams from around the world participated in the 1936 Games, the largest number of participating nations of any Olympics to that point.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Traditionally, the US sent one of the largest teams to the Olympics, and there was a considerable debate over whether the nation should participate in the 1936 Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Americans Milton Green and Norman Cahners refused to attend, and American Jewish organisations, such as the American Jewish Congress and the Jewish Labor Committee, supported a boycott.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Mahoney, president of the Amateur Athletic Union (AAU), contended that racial discrimination was a violation of Olympic rules and that participation in the Games would amount to an indirect endorsement of the Third Reich.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Avery Brundage, then of the American Olympic Committee, opposed the boycott, maintaining that politics had no place in sport and that the Olympic movement would be undermined if nations restricted participation by race or creed.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] After a 1934 fact-finding visit to Germany—conducted largely through Nazi interpreters—Brundage reported that German Jews were not being mistreated.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Most African-American newspapers supported participation in the Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Philadelphia *Tribune* and the *Chicago Defender* both agreed that black victories would undermine Nazi views of Aryan supremacy and spark renewed African-American pride.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Eventually, Brundage won the debate: in December 1935 the Amateur Athletic Union voted narrowly in favour of sending an American team to Berlin, and Mahoney's boycott campaign failed.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The IOC member Ernest Lee Jahncke, who had publicly supported the boycott, was later expelled from the committee and replaced by Brundage.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] US President Franklin Roosevelt and his administration did not become involved in the debate, due to a tradition of allowing the Olympic Committee to operate independently of government influence.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Several American diplomats including William E.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Dodd, the American ambassador to Berlin, and George Messersmith, head of the US legation in Vienna, opposed the decision to participate in the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Jewish Labour Committee staged a "World Labour Athletic Carnival" in New York during the Games as an alternative sporting event.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Spanish government led by the newly elected left-wing Popular Front boycotted the Games and the Government of Catalonia organised the People's Olympiad as a parallel event in Barcelona.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Some 6,000 athletes from 49 countries registered.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] However, the People's Olympiad was aborted because of the outbreak of the Spanish Civil War just one day before the event was due to start.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union had not participated in international sporting events since the 1920 Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Soviet government was not invited to the 1920 Games, with the Russian Civil War still raging, and they did not participate in the 1924 Summer Olympics and forward on ideological grounds.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Instead, through the auspices of the Red Sport International, it had participated in a left-wing workers' alternative, the Spartakiad, since 1928.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The USSR had intended to attend the People's Olympiad in Barcelona until it was cancelled; the Soviets did attend the Spartakiad-sponsored 1937 Workers' Summer Olympiad in Antwerp, Belgium.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union started competing in the Olympics in 1952, when Joseph Stalin realised that they could use the event to fulfil their political and ideological agenda.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] In France, the Jewish fencer Albert Wolff qualified for the national team but withdrew on principle.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Maccabi World Union declined an invitation on behalf of Mandatory Palestine, and two Turkish fencers, Halet Çambel and Suat Fetgeri Aşani—among the first Muslim women to compete at the Olympics—reportedly refused an introduction to Hitler.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Historians widely regard the Berlin Games as a major propaganda success for the Nazi regime, though they differ over how far that success reached.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The US Holocaust Memorial Museum describes them as "a resounding propaganda success" that projected an image of a peaceful, tolerant Germany, and notes that the forty-nine nations who took part lent the regime legitimacy in the eyes of both foreign and domestic audiences.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Most contemporary press coverage was favourable; US newspapers echoed a *New York Times* report that the Games had put Germany "back in the fold of nations".
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Astute diplomats and correspondents stationed in Germany were less easily fooled, but many ordinary visitors and much of the foreign media came away impressed.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Mandell, in the first major English-language study, *The Nazi Olympics* (1971), argued that the regime's unprecedented mass pageantry overwhelmed the critical judgement of visiting journalists, businessmen and diplomats.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Other historians stress that the result turned on the failure of the boycott movement and on the willingness of officials to accept the regime's assurances, rather than on propaganda alone.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Owens's four gold medals became the most enduring popular memory of the Games and were widely seen as a rebuke to Nazi racial theory, though Germany still finished well clear at the top of the medal table.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Owens said he had been treated cordially in Germany and reserved his bitterness for the segregation he faced on returning home, noting that President Franklin Roosevelt neither received nor congratulated him.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The image of a tolerant Germany did not outlast the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Once the foreign visitors had left, anti-Jewish measures resumed and persecution intensified, leading to the Kristallnacht pogrom of November 1938 and, in September 1939, the outbreak of the Second World War.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Several 1936 Olympians were later murdered in the Holocaust, among them the Polish competitors Roman Kantor and Ilia Szrajbman, both killed at Majdanek.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The war forced the cancellation of the 1940 and 1944 Games, and the Olympics did not resume until London 1948.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Games left a lasting cultural and sporting imprint.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Leni Riefenstahl's film *Olympia* (1938) is regarded both as a landmark in cinema—for innovations such as underwater and slow-motion photography that influenced later sports filmmaking—and as a work of state propaganda.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The torch relay and the live television coverage introduced in Berlin became permanent features of the modern Games, and the Olympic Stadium survived the war to be renovated for the 2006 FIFA World Cup final.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] Owens's story has since been dramatised on film, including in *Race* (2016).
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1936-summer-olympics] The Berlin Games are now widely cited as the archetypal example of "sportswashing"—the use of a prestigious sporting event to improve the image of an authoritarian government—and as a precedent in debates over later host selections.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] The **1990 Asian Games**, also known as the **XI Asiad** and the **11th Asian Games** (第十一届亚洲运动会) or simply **Beijing 1990** (北京1990), were held from September 22 to October 7, 1990, in Beijing, China.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] This was the first Asian Games held in China.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] In a fact with precedent, China dominated the games, grabbing 60% of the gold medals and 34% of the total medal count.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] China set a new record by becoming the first nation in the history of the Asian Games to cross the 100-gold medal mark and the 300-total medal mark in one edition.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] This also marked Taiwan's first participation in the Asian Games as Chinese Taipei.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] In 1983, Beijing and Hiroshima demonstrated interest in hosting the 1990 Asian Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] The two cities made formal presentations before the Olympic Council of Asia board.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] They were evaluated in a meeting of the council in Seoul during 1984, which also served to evaluate the preparations for the next Asian Games and also for the 1988 Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] Beijing eventually won the right to host the 1990 edition, while the team from Hiroshima presented an excellent technical bid, and won the rights to host of the 1994 Asian Games as compensation in an unprecedented move.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] To commemorate the 11th Asian Games, three different sets of stamps were issued in 1988, 1989 and 1990.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] The official mascot of this edition was Pan Pan (Chinese: 盼盼), the panda.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] The following venues were used during the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] Yayuncun Subdistrict, the athlete's village was located in Chaoyang District and is now a residential area.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] For the first time, all the participating National Olympic Committees (NOCs) were named according to their official IOC designations and arranged according to their official IOC country codes in 1990.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] Note that Iraq was suspended by the Olympic Council of Asia from participating at the Asian Games due to the Gulf War which killed first OCA president Fahad Al-Ahmed Al-Jaber Al-Sabah.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] Iraq would only return to compete in Doha 2006.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1990-asian-games] The top ten ranked NOCs at these Games are listed below.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Beginning in 1994, the International Olympic Committee decided to hold the Summer and Winter Olympics in alternating even-numbered years.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The 1992 Summer and Winter Olympics were the last games to be staged in the same year.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] These games were the second and last two consecutive Olympic games to be held in Western Europe after the 1992 Winter Olympics in Albertville, France, held five months earlier.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] It is also the second Olympic Games to be held in a Spanish-speaking country, following the 1968 Summer Olympics in Mexico City.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The 1992 Games received universal acclaim, with the organisation, volunteers, sportsmanship, and Spanish public being lauded in the international media.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Some media describe the Barcelona Games as one of the best Olympics ever.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The Games showed a renewed image of a democratic Spain and projected Barcelona and Catalonia to the world.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Owing to the Games, the city of Barcelona was remarkably transformed.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] All the venues are still active, and the legacy of the 1992 Games was taken as an example for future Olympic events, such as London 2012.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The 1992 Summer Games were the first since the end of the Cold War, and the first unaffected by boycotts since the 1972 Summer Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] 1992 was also the first year South Africa was re-invited to the Olympic Games by the International Olympic Committee, after a 32-year ban from participating in international sport due to apartheid.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The Unified Team (made up by the former Soviet republics without the Baltic states) topped the medal table, winning 45 gold and 112 overall medals.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Barcelona was the second-largest city in Spain and the capital of the autonomous community of Catalonia; it is also the hometown of then-IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch and the famous European club FC Barcelona.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The city was also a host for the 1982 FIFA World Cup.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] On 17 October 1986, Barcelona was selected to host the 1992 Summer Olympics over Amsterdam, which hosted the 1928 games; Belgrade, Yugoslavia; Birmingham, United Kingdom; Brisbane, Australia; and Paris, France, during the 91st IOC Session in Lausanne, Switzerland.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] New Delhi, India, had announced a bid for the games, but withdrew in March 1986.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] With 85 out of 89 members of the IOC voting by secret ballot, Barcelona won a majority of 47 votes.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] In the same IOC meeting, Albertville, France, won the right to host the 1992 Winter Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Paris and Brisbane would eventually be selected to host the 2024 and 2032 Summer Olympics respectively.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Barcelona had previously bid for the 1936 Summer Olympics that were ultimately held in Berlin, Germany.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] However, the same day of its planned inauguration (19 July), the Spanish Army carried out a coup d'état which led to the Spanish Civil War.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Facilities of the 1992 Summer Olympics in Barcelona, L'Hospitalet de Llobregat, and Badalona.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] A total of 169 nations sent athletes to compete in the 1992 Summer Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] With the dissolution of the Soviet Union, twelve of the fifteen new states chose to form a Unified Team, while the Baltic States of Estonia and Latvia sent their own teams for the first time since 1936, and Lithuania sent its own team for the first time since 1928.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Bosnia-Herzegovina competed for the first time as an independent nation after its separation from Socialist Yugoslavia, and Namibia and the unified team of Yemen (previously North and South Yemen) also made their Olympic debuts.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Croatia and Slovenia made their first Summer Olympic appearance at these games, having participated at the 1992 Winter Olympics in Albertville.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The 1992 Summer Olympics notably marked Germany competing as a unified team for the first time since 1964 and the first time since 1936 as a single nation following German reunification.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] South Africa returned to the Games for the first time in 32 years.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The Federal Republic of Yugoslavia was banned due to UN sanctions, but individual Yugoslav athletes were allowed to take part as Independent Olympic Participants.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Four then-existing National Olympic Committees did not send any athletes to compete: Afghanistan, Brunei, Liberia and Somalia.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The following table reflects the top ten nations in terms of total medals won at the 1992 Games (the host nation is highlighted).
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] In order to guarantee that the international signal was produced objectively and impartially, for the first time in Olympic history, a host broadcaster was expressly created for each of the 1992 Olympic Games instead of delegating responsibility to a national host broadcaster.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The Albertville Organizing Committee created the Organisme de radio télévision olympique '92 (ORTO'92) for the Winter Olympics and the Barcelona Organizing Committee created the Ràdio Televisió Olímpica '92 (RTO'92) for the Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] RTO'92 managed the staff and the production and technical resources hired to Radiotelevisión Española (RTVE), the Corporació Catalana de Ràdio i Televisió (CCRTV) and the European Broadcasting Union (EBU).
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The International Broadcast Centre (IBC) was located at the exhibition halls of Fira de Barcelona in Montjuïc.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] NHK and Panasonic developed the 1/2" DX digital system used to record the Games digitally for the first time.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] In other countries, broadcast networks secured the rights directly or pooled to secure the rights.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The 1992 Winter and Summer Olympics were the first in which a comprehensive coverage in high-definition television (HDTV) was attempted.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The European HDTV broadcast of the Summer Olympics was managed by the joint venture "Barcelona 1250" created by RTO'92, RTVE, Retevisión and PESA, with the financial support of the European Economic Community and a workforce of over 300 production and technical staff.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Events from five venues were covered live –80% of the total broadcast time– and other events were recorded for a delayed broadcast.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] On-screen text and graphics were shown in HDTV for the first time ever.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Nearly 700 viewing sites installed throughout Europe, including the fifty HDTV receivers installed in various pavilions at the Seville Universal Exposition, were able to receive the broadcast.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] For Japan, NHK also covered the 1992 Summer Olympics in HDTV in their own analog Hi-Vision system.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] 25 of the arrested were kept in solitary confinement.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] They denounced torture at the hands of the Spanish police and threats of violence and rape to them and their families, as well as constant Anti-Catalan and Catalanophobic insults.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Political activists argue that the Spanish State used the Operation Garzón as a tool, under the pretext of security during the Olympic Games, to weaken the left-wing branch of Catalan independence movement.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The Basque nationalist group ETA attempted to disrupt the Barcelona Games with terrorist attacks.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] It was already feared beforehand that ETA would use the Olympics to gain publicity for their cause in front of a worldwide audience.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] As the time of the Games approached, ETA committed attacks in Barcelona and the Catalonia region as a whole, including the deadly 1991 Vic bombing.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] On 10 July 1992, the group offered a two-month truce covering the Olympics in exchange for negotiations, which the Spanish government rejected.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] However, the Games went ahead successfully without an attack.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The celebration of the 1992 Olympic Games had an enormous impact on the urban culture and outward projection of Barcelona, making it a prime example of how hosting a major sporting event can transform a city.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The Games provided billions of dollars for infrastructure investments, which are considered to have improved the quality of life in the city, and its attraction for investment and tourism.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Barcelona became one of the most visited cities in Europe after Paris, London, and Rome.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Barcelona's nomination for the 1992 Summer Olympics sparked the implementation of an ambitious plan for urban transformation that had already been developed previously.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Barcelona was opened to the sea with the construction of the Olympic Village and Olympic Port in Poblenou.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] New centers were created, and modern sports facilities were built in the Olympic zones of Montjuïc, Diagonal, and Vall d'Hebron; hotels were also refurbished and new ones built.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The construction of ring roads around the city helped to reduce traffic density, and El Prat airport was modernized and expanded with the opening of two new terminals.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The *Oxford Olympics Study* estimates the direct costs of the Barcelona 1992 Summer Olympics to be US$9.7 billion (expressed in 2015 U.S. dollars) with a cost overrun of 266%.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Costs *excluded* from the study are indirect capital and infrastructure costs, such as for road, rail, or airport infrastructure, or for hotel upgrades or other business investment incurred in preparation for the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The costs for Barcelona 1992 may be compared with those of London 2012, which cost US$15 billion with a cost overrun of 76%, and those of Rio 2016 which cost US$4.6 billion with a cost overrun of 51%.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The average cost for the Summer Olympics since 1960 is US$5.2 billion, with an average cost overrun of 176%.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] There were two main musical themes for the 1992 Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The first one was "Barcelona", a classical crossover song composed five years earlier by Freddie Mercury and Mike Moran; Mercury was an admirer of lyric soprano Montserrat Caballé, both recorded the official theme as a duet.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Due to Mercury's death eight months earlier, the duo was unable to perform the song together during the opening ceremony.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] A recording of the song instead played over a travelogue of the city at the start of the opening ceremony, seconds before the official countdown.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] "Amigos Para Siempre" (*Friends for Life*) was the other musical theme and it was official theme song of the 1992 Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] It was written by Andrew Lloyd Webber and Don Black, and sung by Sarah Brightman and José Carreras during the closing ceremonies.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] Ryuichi Sakamoto composed and conducted some musical pieces at the opening ceremony musical score.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The Opening Olympic fanfare was composed by Angelo Badalamenti and with orchestrations by Joseph Turrin.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] The official mascot was Cobi, a Catalan sheepdog in cubist style designed by Javier Mariscal.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] He was widely featured in merchandising products and starred his own animated television series, *The Cobi Troupe*.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/1992-summer-olympics] A renewal in Barcelona's image and corporate identity could be seen in the publication of posters, commemorative coins, stamps minted by the FNMT in Madrid, and the Barcelona 1992 Olympic Official Commemorative Medals, designed and struck in Barcelona.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Salt Lake City was selected as the host city in June 1995 at the 104th IOC Session.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] They were the eighth Olympics to be hosted by the United States, and the most recent to be held in the country until 2028, when Los Angeles will host the 34th Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The 2002 Winter Olympics and Paralympics were both organized by the Salt Lake Organizing Committee (SLOC), the first time that both events were organized by a single committee, and inspiring other Olympic and Paralympic Games to be organized by such since then.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] These were the first Olympic Games under the International Olympic Committee (IOC) presidency of Jacques Rogge.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The Games featured 2,399 athletes from 78 nations, participating in 78 events in 15 disciplines.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Norway topped the medal table, with 13 gold and 25 medals overall, while Germany finished with the most total medals, winning 36 (with 12 of them gold).
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The hosting United States was third by gold medals and second by overall medals, with 10 and 34 respectively.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Australia notably became the first Southern Hemisphere country to ever win gold medals at the Winter Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The Games finished with a budgetary surplus of US$40 million; the surplus was used to fund the formation of the Utah Athletic Foundation—which has continued to maintain the facilities built for these Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The venues have continued to be used for national and international winter sports events after the Olympics, leading to the Winter Olympics return to Salt Lake City for the 2034 games, 32 years after the city played host in 2002.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Salt Lake City was chosen over Québec City, Canada; Sion, Switzerland; and Östersund, Sweden, on June 16, 1995, at the 104th IOC Session in Budapest, Hungary.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Salt Lake City had previously come in second during the bids for the 1998 Winter Olympics, awarded to Nagano, Japan, and had offered to be the provisional host of the 1976 Winter Olympics when the original host, Denver, Colorado, withdrew.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The 1976 Winter Olympics were ultimately awarded to Innsbruck, Austria.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] There was a scandal involving allegations of bribery used to win the rights to the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Prior to its successful bid, Salt Lake City had attempted four times to secure the games, failing each time.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] In 1998, members of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) were accused of taking gifts from the Salt Lake Organizing Committee (SLOC) during the bidding process.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The allegations resulted in the expulsion of several IOC members and the adoption of new IOC rules.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Although nothing strictly illegal had been done, it was felt that the acceptance of the gifts was morally dubious.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] In addition, legal charges were brought against the leaders of Salt Lake's bid committee by the United States Department of Justice.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Investigations were also launched into prior bidding process by other cities, finding that members of the IOC received bribes during the bidding process for both the 1998 Winter Olympics and 2000 Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] In response to the scandal, Mitt Romney was hired as the new president and CEO of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee in February 1999.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] In February 1999, in response to the bid scandal and a financial shortfall for the Games, Mitt Romney, then CEO of the private equity firm Bain Capital (and future U.S. presidential candidate, U.S.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Senator, and Governor of Massachusetts), was hired as the new president and CEO of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] An additional US$410 million was received from the federal government.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] U.S. federal subsidies amounted to $1.3 billion (for infrastructure improvements only), compared to $45 billion of federal funding received by the organizing committee of the 2014 Winter Olympics from the Russian government.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The Games were financially successful, raising more money with fewer sponsors than any prior Olympic Games, which left SLOC with a surplus of $40 million.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The surplus was used to create the Utah Athletic Foundation, which maintains and operates many of the remaining Olympic venues.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The 2002 Winter Games were the first Olympic Games to take place since the September 11 attacks, which meant a higher level of security than ever before provided for the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] As a result, the Office of Homeland Security (OHS) designated the Olympics a National Special Security Event (NSSE).
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Aerial surveillance and radar control was provided by the U.S.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Marines of Marine Air Control Squadron 2, Detachment C, from Cherry Point, North Carolina.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The FBI and NSA arranged with Qwest Communications to use intercept equipment for a period of less than six months around the time of the 2002 Winter Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The largest public transport project completed for the Games was the TRAX light rail system, which first began operations ahead of the Games in 1999.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] To help reduce vehicle traffic to Soldier Hollow, and to provide a tourist attraction for attendees, Heber Valley Railroad offered service to Wasatch Mountain State Park on steam locomotives during the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] After arriving, passengers then embarked to Soldier Hollow on horse-drawn sleighs.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Work on venues for the 2002 Winter Olympics began as early as 1989, following the passing of a state referendum that authorized the use of taxpayer money to publicly fund the construction of new facilities for a Winter Olympics bid in 1998 or 2002.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Their construction was overseen by the Salt Lake Olympic Bid Committee and the Utah Sports Authority—a body created under the referendum.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] New facilities built for the Games included the Utah Olympic Oval in Kearns, Utah Olympic Park in Summit County, The Ice Sheet at Ogden, and Soldier Hollow at the Wasatch Mountain State Park—the furthest competition venue from Salt Lake City.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The E Center in West Valley City and the Peaks Ice Arena in Provo were also built with support from the SLOC, and co-hosted hockey.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Delta Center hosted figure skating and short track speed skating; it was renamed *Salt Lake Ice Center* for the duration of the Games due to IOC sponsorship rules.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Rice-Eccles Stadium at the University of Utah hosted the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The Olympic Village was built at historic Fort Douglas, whose land had been acquired by the University of Utah to construct new residences.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The SLOC provided funding to the project in exchange for its use during the Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Main Street in Park City was converted into a pedestrian plaza during the Games, with festivities such as concerts, firework shows, and sponsor presences.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Medal presentations took place in downtown Salt Lake City; the stage for the ceremony featured the Hoberman Arch, an arch-shaped metal "curtain" designed by Chuck Hoberman.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The 2002 Cultural Olympiad, which ran from January to March 2002, was an arts festival that accompanied the 2002 Winter Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] It included specially commissioned works, such as Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater's work *Here...Now* inspired by the life of Olympian Florence Griffith Joyner, accompanied by music by Wynton Marsalis.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] An art exhibition was held at Springville Museum of Art that celebrated 150 years of Utah's art history.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The programme also featured many other performances, including dance, theatre, singing, and literature, as well as the glass art of Dale Chihuly.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Call of the Champions is a cantata-fanfare for orchestra and choir composed by John Williams for the 2002 Winter Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Premiering at the Opening Ceremony on February 8, 2002, it began with the call by the Tabernacle Choir at Temple Square of "Citius!
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Fortius!" (Faster, Higher, Stronger), which is the Olympic Motto chosen by the founder of the modern Games, Baron Pierre de Coubertin.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The torch relay ceremonially began on November 19, 2001, with the traditional kindling of an Olympic flame in Olympia, Greece.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] On December 3, Greek skier Thanassis Tsailas lit the first torch from the cauldron, and transferred its flame to a ceremonial lantern for transport to Atlanta, where it arrived on December 4 to officially launch the U.S. leg of the relay.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The route of the relay covered 13,500 miles (21,700 km), passed through 300 communities and 46 U.S. states, and was carried by 12,012 torchbearers.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The torch was modeled after an icicle, with a slight curve to represent speed and fluidity.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The torch measures 33 inches (84 cm) long, 3 inches (7.6 cm) wide at the top, 0.5 inches (1.3 cm) at the bottom, and was designed by Axiom Design of Salt Lake City.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] It was created with three sections, each with its own meaning and representation.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The overall branding of the 2002 Winter Olympics, the "Look of the Games" design was named "Land of Contrast — Fire and Ice", which featured a palette of warm and cool colors to contrast the warmer, rugged, red-rock areas of Southern Utah from the colder, mountainous regions of Northern Utah.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The three main color palettes were: *Amber Gold*, *Sunset Orange* and *Mountain Shadow Blue*: With accented hue variations of the palette.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] It featured a six pointed snow crystal, again with the three main colors representing Utahs southern deserts and its high snowy mountain ranges.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Designed to resemble an Olympic cauldron, a flame, as well as a sun rising from behind mountains.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The orange center section of the flame was intended to reflect traditional Navajo weaving.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The emblem logo was designed by Landor Associates and unveiled in August 1997.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The official event pictograms were inspired by branding irons, and the line thickness and 30-degree angles mirrored those of the emblem.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The designs of the mascots of the 2002 Winter Olympics were unveiled on May 19, 1999, during an event marking 1,000 days until the opening ceremony.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] For the first time in Olympic history, the names of the mascots were determined by a public vote, using name suggestions submitted by local students; on September 25, the names of the mascots were officially announced as Powder, Copper, and Coal respectively.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] A total of 78 teams qualified at least one athlete to compete in the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Five NOCs made their Winter Olympic debut in Salt Lake, including Cameroon, Hong Kong, Nepal, Tajikistan, and Thailand.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Costa Rica and Lebanon returned to the Winter games after a 10-year absence, and Fiji, Mexico and San Marino returned after 8 years.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Four countries, Luxembourg, North Korea, Portugal and Uruguay which were at the 1998 Games, did not participate in 2002.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] In the following calendar for the 2002 Winter Olympic Games, each blue box represents an event competition, such as a qualification round, on that day.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The yellow boxes represent days during which medal-awarding finals for a sport are held.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The number in each box represents the number of finals that were contested on that day.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The opening ceremony of the 2002 Winter Olympics was held at Rice–Eccles Stadium at the University of Utah on February 8, 2002.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The facility was renovated and expanded for the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The Games were officially opened by President George W.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The flag was presented during the playing of the U.S. national anthem "The Star-Spangled Banner", as performed by the Tabernacle Choir.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The Olympic cauldron was designed to look like an icicle and was made of glass, allowing the fire to be seen burning within, reflecting the Games' slogan "Light the Fire Within" and an overarching "fire and ice" theme.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The actual glass cauldron stands atop a twisting glass and steel support, is 12 feet (3.7 m) high, and the flame within burns at 900 °F (482 °C).
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Together with its support, the cauldron stands 117 feet (36 m) tall and was made of 738 individual pieces of glass.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Small jets send water down the glass sides of the cauldron to keep the glass and metal cooled (so they would not crack or melt) and give the effect of melting ice.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The cauldron was designed by WET Design of Los Angeles, its frame built by roller coaster manufacturer Arrow Dynamics of Clearfield, Utah, and its glass pieces created by Western Glass of Ogden, Utah.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The cauldron's cost was $2 million, and it was unveiled to the public when originally installed at Rice–Eccles Stadium on January 8, 2002.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Production for the opening and closing ceremonies was designed by Seven Nielsen, and music for both ceremonies was directed by Mark Watters.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The closing ceremony of the 2002 Winter Olympics was held on February 24, 2002, at Rice–Eccles Stadium.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Kelly, Sting, Willie Nelson, and Yo Yo Ma.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] It also featured appearances by figure skaters such as Kurt Browning, Dorothy Hamill, and Ilia Kulick, as well as dancer Savion Glover.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Departing from Juan Antonio Samaranch's tradition of declaring each Olympics the "best ever", IOC president Jacques Rogge began a tradition of assigning each Games their own identity in his comments, describing the 2002 Winter Olympics as having been "flawless".
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Italian singers Irene Grandi and Elisa performed during the cultural presentation by Turin, host city of the 2006 Winter Olympics, while Josh Groban and Charlotte Church performed a duet of "The Prayer" as the Olympic cauldron was extinguished.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Confirmed in 1997, this edition's sports program featured seven sports divided into 15 disciplines, totaling 78 events, an increase of 10 events over the 1998 Winter Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Skeleton made its return to the Winter Olympic program for the first time since 1948, while a women's doubles event was contested for the first time in bobsleigh.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] A fourth distance was introduced in short track speed skating for men and women, and the pursuit events were added to biathlon and cross-country skiing.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The sprint event was also added to the Nordic combined program.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] At the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City, the "medal plaza" was popularized as a way for the public to see presentations that would have otherwise taken place at far-flung, low-capacity or high-altitude venues and to have an evening program that often included musical performances.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] International Sports Broadcasting (ISB) served as the host broadcaster for the 2002 Winter Olympics; the Salt Palace convention center served as the International Broadcast Centre and press center for the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The IOC estimated that the 2002 Winter Olympics were viewed by over two billion people worldwide, with 13 billion viewer-hours watched.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] In the United States, the 2002 Winter Olympics were broadcast by NBC Universal networks.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] They were the first Winter Olympics under a multi-year rights agreement between NBC and the IOC, under which it would hold exclusive rights to all Olympic Games from 1996 through 2008.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The contract had excluded the 1998 Winter Olympics, as CBS Sports had an existing deal to exclusively televise the Winter Olympics from 1992 through 1998.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] NBC partnered with HDNet to produce an eight-hour block of daily coverage in high definition, which was carried by HDNet and on the digital signals of participating NBC affiliates.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Coverage of the Games by the Seven Network in Australia featured *The Ice Dream*, a miniseries presented by comedy duo Roy and HG as a follow-up to *The Dream*—their series for the 2000 Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The series featured a running gag of the duo proposing an Australian bid to hold the 2010 Winter Olympics in the resort town of Smiggin Holes, New South Wales.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The 2002 Winter Olympics brought a huge amount of success to the Utah skiing industry.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Since hosting the Winter Games, Utah has seen a 42% increase in skier and snowboarder visits as of 2010–11.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] This increase resulted in direct expenditures from skiers and snowboarders growing 67% from $704 million in 2002–2003 to $1.2 billion in 2010–2011.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Fourteen venues were constructed or expanded in preparation for the Winter Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] One of the venues constructed for the Games was the Utah Olympic Park, which has proven to be one of the most successful venues to date because it has been maintained in top competition form.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Owing to the routine maintenance of the park, Utah has been able to host a large number of winter competitions since 2002, including more than 60 World Cup events (e.g. the FIS Freestyle Skiing World Cup), as well as seven world championships, and various other sporting events.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Hosting these high-profile competitions has resulted in approximately $1 billion being injected into the local economy.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] During 2013–2014, Utah held 16 various winter sport events, bringing $27.3 million to the economy of Utah.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] After holding the Olympics, Utah became home to two National Governing Bodies of Sport.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Ski and Snowboard Association is headquartered in Park City, Utah and the U.S.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Olympic speed skating team is based out of the Utah Olympic Oval.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The University of Utah was one of the hosts of the 2002 Winter Olympics; the planning committee approached the University of Utah and asked them to build several student dormitories which would serve as athletes' accommodation during the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] It was agreed that the university would pay approximately $98 million out of the total required amount of $110 million to complete the construction.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] As a result, students of the university have benefited as almost 3,500 of them would be housed here after the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] This was a great economic benefit to the university since the amount of money used to complete such dormitories could take long to be afforded.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The university was also asked to expand Rice Eccles Stadium to accommodate 50,000 people up from 32,000.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The university would then be refunded almost $59 million and be given an extra $40 million for its maintenance.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The 2002 Olympic Games also benefited the university economically since the Salt Lake 2002 Olympic Cauldron Park was elevated by the renovations that took place.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Ice rinks were very scarce in Utah, but they became plentiful and offered several entertainment and training opportunities for hockey players and figure skaters due to the Olympic Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Besides, the park had 17 plates that hung on the stadium's fence celebrating the highlights of each day of the Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] All these features acted as tourist attraction that boosted the economic development of the university.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] In addition, it is indicated that the approximate value of media exposure through print during the Games was equated to $22.9 million.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Mainly, this was a huge economic benefit to the university as more and more people got to know about the educational establishment, and this also boosted enrollment and future development.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] It was noted that the increase of Olympic related job started in 1996 and continued until 2003.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] These effects can be estimated on the ground of historical relationship between job and corresponding population growth.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] A lot of people migrated into the future place of the Olympic Games for expanding and favorable employment opportunities that the Olympics ensured.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Although residents occupied many of the higher paying jobs created by the Games, many of the vacated jobs were filled by immigrants who relocated for the better employment opportunities.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Basically, the immigration rate was even larger because the employees immigrated with their families.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The additional people paid diverse taxes and fees from their income, creating additional revenue on the state and local levels.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Olympic related jobs in Utah started in 1996 with slight job opportunities of less than 100.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] However, from the job measurement conducted from 1996 to 2002, steady attainment of job opportunities established and a maximum level was noted in 2001 where there were 12,500 job opportunities attained yearly, and approximately 25,070 jobs created in 2002.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Therefore, from 1996 to 2002 the sum of employment equated to 35,000 jobs which lasted a year.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] February 2002 is when the highest employment opportunities were created compared to other years.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] There were around 25,070 job opportunities created compared to 35,000 created from 1996 to 2001.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] It is difficult to quantify the impact of the 2002 Olympics on the unemployment rates in Utah, due mostly to the effect of the early 2000s recession.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] In 1996, the unemployment rate in Utah was approximately 3.4%, while the U.S. national average was 5.4% and by the end of 2001, the unemployment rate in Utah was around 4.8%, while the national average had risen to 5.7%.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] There was a high percentage of visitors to the Games, which raised the number of tourists whose consumption and demand prompted the establishment of job opportunities to meet the demands.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] In 2017, an exploratory committee was formed to consider a Salt Lake City bid for a future Winter Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] In December 2018, the United States Olympic Committee (USOC, now the United States Olympic & Paralympic Committee [USOPC]) named Salt Lake City as its preferred candidate to bid for a future Winter Olympics, citing that its experience and existing venues could be leveraged.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] On July 24, 2024, during the 142nd IOC Session in Paris just before the 2024 Summer Olympics in that city, Salt Lake City–Utah was selected to host the 2034 Winter Olympics and Paralympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] IOC President Thomas Bach said: "Salt Lake City and Utah are long-time friends of the Olympic Movement, and we are confident that they will organize exceptional Olympic and Paralympic Games, just as they did years ago.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The legacy of 2002 is tangibly and passionately alive in Utah.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The legacy of 2034 starts today." With the 2034 Winter Olympics, Salt Lake City will become the fourth city to host multiple Winter Games after Innsbruck (1964 and 1976), Lake Placid (1932 and 1980), and Cortina d'Ampezzo (1956 and 2026).
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The 2002 Winter Olympics were the first Winter Olympics held after the formation of the World Anti-Doping Agency, resulting in the first instances of athletes being disqualified for failing drug testing.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Athletes in cross-country skiing were disqualified for various reasons, including doping by two Russians and one Spaniard, leading Russia to file protests and threaten to withdraw from the competition.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] A major scandal emerged during the pairs figure skating competition; the Canadian pair of Jamie Salé and David Pelletier narrowly lost to the Russian pair of Elena Berezhnaya and Anton Sikharulidze, despite the Canadians being deemed the favorites to win after their free skate program.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The French judge Marie-Reine Le Gougne alleged that the head of the French Federation of Ice Sports, Didier Gailhaguet, had pressured her to judge the competition in favor of Russia regardless of performance.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] They also recommended to the IOC that the gold medal be jointly awarded to both pairs.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] An IOC panel voted in favor of the motion, resulting in both Salé and Pelletier, as well as Berezhnaya and Sikharulidze, being jointly awarded gold medals.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] In the final race A, with one lap remaining and currently in second place, Apolo Ohno of the United States attempted to make a pass on the leader Kim Dong-Sung of South Korea, who then drifted to the inside and as a result, Ohno raised his arms to imply he was blocked.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] Kim finished first ahead of Ohno, but the Australian referee James Hewish disqualified Kim for what appeared to be impeding, awarding the gold medal to Ohno.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The South Korean team immediately protested the decision of the chief official of the race, but their protests were denied by the International Skating Union (ISU).
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The South Korean team then appealed to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and the Court of Arbitration for Sport (CAS).
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The IOC refused to see the case, stating, "This is a matter for the ISU to decide on.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] At this time, the IOC has received no proposal and taken no action".
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The disqualification of Kim upset South Korean supporters, many of whom directed their anger at Ohno and the IOC.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] A large number of e-mails protesting the race results crashed the IOC's email server, and thousands of accusatory letters, many of which contained death threats, were sent to Ohno and the IOC.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] South Korean media accused Ohno of simulating foul, using the Konglish word "Hollywood action".
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] The controversy continued at the 2002 FIFA World Cup, held jointly in South Korea and Japan several months after the Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2002-winter-olympics] When the South Korean soccer team scored a goal during the group stage match against the U.S. team, South Korean players Ahn Jung-Hwan and Lee Chun-Soo made an exaggerated move imitating the move Ohno had made during the speed skating event to imply the other athlete had drifted into his lane.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2005-national-games-of-china] The **10th National Games of the People's Republic of China** was a multi-sport event that was held in Nanjing City, Jiangsu Province, from 12–23 October 2005.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2005-national-games-of-china] This was the first time the National Games was hosted by a province outside of Beijing, Shanghai, and Guangdong, which had hosted the games on a rotational basis.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2005-national-games-of-china] As a premier national sporting event, **the 10th National Games of the People's Republic of China** aimed to identify and nurture athlete talents and build up the national teams for the 2008 Olympic Games in Beijing.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2005-national-games-of-china] There were a total of 32 events at the 10th National Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2005-national-games-of-china] Medals of athletes of every team received in 2004 Olympics and 2002 Winter Olympics are taken into the medal count of that team.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2007-world-wushu-championships] The **2007 World Wushu Championships** was the 9th edition of the World Wushu Championships.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2007-world-wushu-championships] It was held at the Olympic Sports Center Gymnasium in Beijing, China from November 11 to November 17, 2007.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2007-world-wushu-championships] Nearly 1,000 athletes from 89 IWUF national federations participated in the event.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2007-world-wushu-championships] The competition also acted as a qualifier for the 2008 Beijing Wushu Tournament and the 2009 World Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament-men-s-changquan] The men's changquan competition at the 2008 Beijing Wushu Tournament was held on August 22 at the Olympic Sports Center Gymnasium.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament-men-s-changquan] The favorite of the competition, Yuan Xiaochao, had been undefeated in changquan in international competitions since 2005 which included gold medal victories at the World Wushu Championships, the Asian Games, and at the East Asian Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament-men-s-changquan] Aung Si Thu and Ang Eng Chong were also projected favorites as they were the silver and bronze medalists respectively at the 2007 World Wushu Championships.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament-men-s-changquan] At the Beijing Wushu Tournament, Yuan Xiaochao clearly dominated the competition with a wide margin and thus won the gold medal.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament-men-s-changquan] The silver medalist Semen Udelov and bronze medalist Ehsan Peighambari impressed with their performances as Udelov ranked 7th and Peighambari ranked 24th at the 2007 World Wushu Championships.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament-men-s-changquan] Both athletes were also selected through the wild card process by Russia and Iran respectively since they did not originally qualify by placing in the top six.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament-men-s-changquan] Daisuke Ichikizaki, who was another close contender, missed the silver medal due to a 0.1 deduction.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament-men-s-changquan] The event was judged with the degree of difficulty component.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] The **2008 Beijing Wushu Tournament** (Chinese: 北京2008武术比赛; pinyin: *Běijīng 2008 wǔshù bǐsài*) was a wushu competition which was held from August 21 to 24, 2008 at the Olympic Sports Center Gymnasium in Beijing, China.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] The tournament was organised by the Beijing Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games (BOCOG), the International Wushu Federation (IWUF), and the Chinese Wushu Association (CWA), and was held in tandem with the 2008 Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] The competition consisted of ten taolu events (5 male, 5 female), and five sanshou events (3 male, 2 female).
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] The Chinese team dominated the competition with eight gold medals followed by Russia and Hong Kong which earned two gold medals each.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] Macau, Iran and the Philippines each won a single gold.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] Wushu's first Olympic appearance was at the 1936 Summer Olympics as an unofficial exhibition event.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] Starting in the 1970s, the government of the People's Republic of China started to consider sport as a possible medium for friendly international exchange.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] One sport the PRC was very interested in developing was modern wushu.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] In 1982, the General Administration of Sport of China officially proclaimed that wushu practitioners had a duty 'to promote wushu to the world' with the ultimate goal of wushu becoming an official event at the Olympic Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] The International Wushu Federation (IWUF) was founded 1990 Asian Games, and over a decade later, it was fully recognised by the International Olympic Committee during the 113th IOC Congress at the 2002 Winter Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] This development along with Beijing's successful bid in hosting the 2008 Olympics presented the opportunity for wushu to be included in the Games, but as Jacques Rogge became the new president of the IOC in 2002, he announced the IOC's plans to reduce the number of the events at the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] This led to the creation of the Olympic Programme Commission which called for changes and reevaluations within the Olympic programme.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] Despite this, the Beijing Organising Committee for the Olympic Games (BOCOG), the IWUF, and the Chinese Wushu Association (CWA) began to lobby extensively for the official inclusion of wushu.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] Athletes and organisations argued that the inclusion of the sport would help culturally diversify the Games and hoped that wushu would follow the same Olympic path as judo and taekwondo.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] In August 2002, the Olympic Programme Commission under Chairman Franco Carraro recommended to the IOC executive board that wushu should not be admitted to the 2008 Summer Olympics, and reasoned that it was not a sport of global appeal and that it would add no substantial value to the Games.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] Shortly after this meeting though, the IOC reversed their decision and stated that the sport of wushu was once again under consideration.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] In 2004, the Olympic Programme Commission introduced new evaluation criteria for Olympic sports to ensure the events would be fair and of high quality.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] As a result, the IWUF switched to computerised scoring and the *International Rules for Taolu Competition* were significantly revised.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] Sanshou rules stayed relatively the same besides switching to computerised scoring.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] In 2005, IOC President Rogge met with the IWUF President and IOC executive board member Yu Zaiqing at the Chinese Grand Prix and announced that wushu will have no place in the Olympic Games in Beijing, not even as a demonstration sport.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] After meeting again a few weeks later at the 2005 National Games of China, all parties involved came to a compromise.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] Other than substituting the Olympic rings with the logo of the IWUF, all other elements (e.g. medal design, award presentation & ceremony, graphic elements and colours, volunteers of the tournament, etc.) were identical to the Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] Athletes were also allowed to stay in the athletes' village though were only allowed to arrive only a few days before the tournament.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] The official BOCOG website also included the schedule, results, and profiles of the athletes.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] Day two of the competition was broadcast on China Central Television (CCTV) but other international channels provided live streaming for other days.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] The taolu and sanda events took place at the Olympic Sports Center Gymnasium, which was the site for the Handball competition at the 2008 Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] The Beijing Wushu Tournament borrowed the same combined-event format which was seen at wushu competitions such as the Asian Games, Southeast Asian Games, and the National Games of China.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] 128 athletes from 43 countries took part in the Beijing Wushu Tournament.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] National federations were not allowed to send more than eight taolu and sanshou athletes to the competition.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] Since China was the hosting nation, any of its athletes which competed at the 2007 world championships would qualify.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] Unlike the IOC, the IWUF recognises the Macau Olympic Committee and athletes representing Macau were allowed to compete in the competition.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] Besides the typical awarding of medals per each taolu event at the 2007 world championships, all athletes were ranked based on their combined scores from the proposed events at the Beijing Wushu Tournament (ie. daoshu and gunshu; jianshu and qiangshu; etc.).
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] All athletes which ranked within the top six of a combined category or changquan (as ranking was done based only on the singular event) qualified for the Beijing Wushu Tournament.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] The IWUF then distributed 20 wild cards to various national federations to send more athletes.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] A national federation could enter only one athlete per each event and all athletes could compete in only one event.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] As Chinese athletes at the 2007 world championships would automatically qualify for the Beijing Wushu Tournament, all of them opted not to participate in their second events after winning gold medals in their first events.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] All sanshou athletes who placed in the top eight in the selected events for this competition (men's 56 kg, 70 kg or 80 kg; women's 52 kg or 60 kg) at the 2007 world championships qualified for the tournament.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] Vacancies due to illness, injury, or nonavailability were not filled, hence the unusual distribution of participants and rounds.
[src:2008-beijing-wushu-tournament/2008-beijing-wushu-tournament] Since the Beijing Wushu Tournament was not officially connected to the Olympic Games, medals earned were not added to the official Olympics medal tally.
